04384nam a22005415i 9780226253978DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014044823  a97802262539787 a10.7208/97802262539782doi  a(DE-B1597)550189  a(OCoLC)910847959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aP91b.P48 2015 4aP91b.P48 2015 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a302.2/01223  aAP 135502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/6883:1 aPeters, John Durham, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Marvelous Clouds :bToward a Philosophy of Elemental Media /cJohn Durham Peters. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b2 halftones, 4 line drawings, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: In Medias Res -- tChapter 1. Understanding Media -- tChapter 2. Of Cetaceans and Ships; or, The Moorings of Our Being -- tChapter 3. The Fire Sermon -- tChapter 4. Lights in the Firmament: Sky Media I (Chronos) -- tChapter 5. The Times and the Seasons: Sky Media II (Kairos) -- tChapter 6. The Face and the Book (Inscription Media) -- tChapter 7. God and Google -- tConclusion. The Sabbath of Meaning -- tAppendix: Nonsimultaneity in Cetacean Communication -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen we speak of clouds these days, it is as likely that we mean data clouds or network clouds as cumulus or stratus. In their sharing of the term, both kinds of clouds reveal an essential truth: that the natural world and the technological world are not so distinct. In The Marvelous Clouds, John Durham Peters argues that though we often think of media as environments, the reverse is just as true—environments are media. Peters defines media expansively as elements that compose the human world. Drawing from ideas implicit in media philosophy, Peters argues that media are more than carriers of messages: they are the very infrastructures combining nature and culture that allow human life to thrive. Through an encyclopedic array of examples from the oceans to the skies, The Marvelous Clouds reveals the long prehistory of so-called new media. Digital media, Peters argues, are an extension of early practices tied to the establishment of civilization such as mastering fire, building calendars, reading the stars, creating language, and establishing religions. New media do not take us into uncharted waters, but rather confront us with the deepest and oldest questions of society and ecology: how to manage the relations people have with themselves, others, and the natural world. A wide-ranging meditation on the many means we have employed to cope with the struggles of existence—from navigation to farming, meteorology to Google—The Marvelous Clouds shows how media lie at the very heart of our interactions with the world around us. Peters’s book will not only change how we think about media but provide a new appreciation for the day-to-day foundations of life on earth that we so often take for granted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCommunicationxPhilosophy. 0aInternet. 0aWritten communication. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226253978423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226253978.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles